                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d205">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.01/11–1549: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Second Secretary of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bacon</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-11-15T09:00:00+08:00"
                            >November 15, 1949—9 a. m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received November 14—11:03 p. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2427. ReDepintel November 10.<note n="23" xml:id="d205fn23">Not printed; it
                        reported on the Singapore conference (800.00 Summaries/11–1049).</note> Our
                    impression is that Titoism arose in Yugoslavia not because of any action or
                    failure to act on part of Western Powers, but as direct results of action
                    injurious to Yugoslav political independence and economic reconstruction. We
                    consider estrangement between China and USSR will probably arise in same way and
                    our recognition at this time could contribute little or nothing to this
                    development.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bacon</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
